WLEDGE: -- t15. "Women come here on their own when they need to" -- t16. Maternal Health, War, and Religious Tradition -- t17. Heeding Warnings from the Canary, the Whale, and the Inuit -- t18. An Ideal of Unassisted Birth -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis benchmark collection of cross-cultural essays on reproduction and childbirth extends and enriches the work of Brigitte Jordan, who helped generate and define the field of the anthropology of birth. The authors' focus on authoritative knowledge—the knowledge that counts, on the basis of which decisions are made and actions taken—highlights the vast differences between birthing systems that give authority of knowing to women and their communities and those that invest it in experts and machines.Childbirth and Authoritative Knowledge offers first-hand ethnographic research conducted by anthropologists in sixteen different societies and cultures and includes the interdisciplinary perspectives of a social psychologist, a sociologist, an epidemiologist, a staff member of the World Health Organization, and a community midwife. Exciting directions for further research as well as pressing needs for policy guidance emerge from these illuminating explorations of authoritative knowledge about birth. This book is certain to follow Jordan's Birth in Four Cultures as the definitive volume in a rapidly expanding field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBirth customs. 0aChildbirthvCross-cultural studies. 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aalternative models.  aanthropology of birth.  aanthropology.  aauthority.  abiomedical hegemony.  abirth territory.  abirth.  achildbirth.  acommunity midwife.  